<article>
  <header>
    <h1><a href="/2026/06/29/the-agent-will-not-ask/" rel="bookmark">The agent will not ask</a></h1>
  </header>
  <section>
    <p>When a developer doesn’t know which button variant to use for a destructive action, they can ask. An agent composing UI on the fly isn’t going to ask. It works from what you give it — component names, tokens, usage rules — and produces something.</p>
    <p>Humans are good at inferring intent; agents take you literally.</p>
  </section>
  <footer>
    <p class="posted-on"><time datetime="2026-06-29">Jun 29, 2026</time></p>
  </footer>
</article>

<article>
  <header>
    <h1><a href="/2026/06/08/quick-prototypes-beat-thinking/" rel="bookmark">Quick prototypes beat thinking your way to one answer</a></h1>
  </header>
  <section>
    <p>A product team needed to decide if and how to provide a little convenience around an API Name when their user enters a Display Name. Small interaction, lots of edge cases.</p>
    <p>In the old way of working, a designer would think about the possibilities, propose something to the team, there’d be an argument, and eventually something would ship.</p>
  </section>
  <footer>
    <p class="posted-on"><time datetime="2026-06-08">Jun 8, 2026</time></p>
  </footer>
</article>

